<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Ragon der Magier on 11-21-1999 12:01 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Hi there!

I´d rather suggest presenting the 'unbloody' solutions as preferable to the player by
- of course rewarding the smartest solutions with the most XPs
- giving incentives to avoid fighting, let´s say for more experienced players the fight against a small group of orcs is no challenge anymore, but persuading the enemies not to fight might perhaps result in a more useful favor from them in the future or better reputation at their folks. Or present a peaceful resolution of conflict as a quicker way to resume the current journey rather than a while surely winnable combat but nevertheless time consuming. Another reason could be the knowledge of a more demanding opponent after this encounter, which allows not the slightest blood drain in the party (or from the single character, whatever it´ll be) , as all power, health and ressources (health/mana potions etc.) have to be preserved for that decisive duel). Or the party (single) is tracked by hostile troops anyway or has a quest that requires as discrete proceding as possible which of course includes any unnecessary battling.
- reward the x´th slayer of a goblin tribe with no XPs anymore at all, but still give opportunity for XP-gain throughout the more advanced solutions
- order of XP-rewarding: Hack´n´slay - least, soon none
make adversaries flee - more
negotiate a bloodless solution - even more
befriend a troll with music or treats - most
instead of killing persuade the encounter to give an item, give interesting informations, join temporarily party aso (and so on) -    unbelievably much and rising  ;).

There are more than enough possibilities to replace fighting in game situations if one thinks about it for awhile. But it´s late now and my brain starts floating away. But you have surely enough left (i hope at least  ;)), think on for yourself.

May Madas silver sign watch over you and beware you from the evils that lurk in the night

Ragon the mage</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
